04594nam a22007575i 9789814762380DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162016si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898147623807 a10.1355/97898147623802doi  a(DE-B1597)522139  a(OCoLC)1096436646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0400002bisacsh1 aWinichakul, Thongchai, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThailand's Hyper-royalism :bIts Past Success and Present Predicament /cThongchai Winichakul. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (36 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tThailand’s Hyper-royalism: Its Past Success and Present Predicament -- tHISTORICAL BACKGROUND -- tCHARACTERISTICS -- tCONCEPT: THE IDEAL MODERN MONARCHY -- tSPELLS: THE RIGHTEOUS MONARCHY FOR ALL PEOPLE -- tMAGIC: VISUAL ILLUSION OF SACRED MONARCHY -- tCRISIS AND DISENCHANTMENT -- tPREDICAMENT -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThailand’s political impasse in the past decade is partly attributable to the royalist dominance of the parliamentary system, a dominance developed and strengthened under the cultural condition of hyper-royalism. Hyper-royalism is the politico-cultural condition in which royalism is intensified and exaggerated in public and everyday life. It is sanctioned by legislation that controls expressions about the monarchy in the public sphere. Hyper-royalism began in the mid-1970s as a measure to counteract perceived communist threats. Despite the fact that these threats had disappeared by the early 1980s, hyper-royalism persisted and was strengthened to support royalist democracy. Hyper-royalism generates the concept of the ideology of modern monarchy — a charismatic king who is sacred, righteous and cares for his people, and who is indispensable to Thailand — and the belief that royalist democracy is best for Thailand. Hyper-royalism also generates the illusion that the monarchy is divine, thanks to visual performances and objects, especially through television and majestic pageantry. Accordingly, the ideal monarch is found in King Bhumibol. Given the mortality of Bhumibol, however, future prospects of hyper-royalism and royalist-guided democracy are grim. Thailand’s political future is highly uncertain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGovernment. 0aMonarchy—Thailand. 0aThailand—Politics and government. 4aGovernment. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066299308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070101240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981476238040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814762380423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814762380.jpg  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066299-3  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070101-2  PP Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK